        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "Not Applicable",
          "End of Program Graduation or Dropout",
          "Dropped out (0) vs Graduated (1)",
          "15825 undergraduate students",
          "All courses in a Hungarian University",
          "Enrollment data, \nHighschool Academic History, Student Characteristics",
          "[Student ID, Program ID, Year of Enrollment, Faculty of Program, Field of Program, Financial Status, High School ID, Name of Highschool, Type of Educational Institute, City and County, Admission points score, Study points, Matura exam points, Extra points, Base Points, Hungarian Language Matura Exam, MAths Matura Exam, History Matura Exam, Foreign Language Matura Exam, Language, Language Level, Consortium, Competition Achievement, APS calculating method, Gender, Data of Birth, Address]",
          "Admission of Student",
          "Authors are required to adopt multiple pre-processing steps (imputation of nans, Feature Selection, etc…). Comparison of ddifferent Nan imputation strategies is performed.\n\nFeature Engineering creates 4 families of variables: \n- Student ID\n- Highschool-Related, \n- Highschool Performance Related,\n- Personal details.\n\n \n\n",
          "DT\nRandom Forest\nGeneralized Linear Model\nNaive Bayes\nAdaBoost\nkNN\nLogistic Regression\nGBoost\nDeep Learning",
          "10-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "{AUC: 0.811 - Deep Learning, Accuracy: 0.735 - Deep Learning, Recall: 0.897 - DT, Precision: 0.708 - Deep Learning}",
          "Authors do Early Prediction of Dropout by using only information that should be available at the time of admission of a learner.\n\nAuthors compare different forms of filling missing-values - Nans filled using kNN imputation outperformed the alternative preprocessing methods.\n\nPrsopective studfents can provide their details and receive a prediction.",
          "Only uses admission data.\n\nA lot of the information is extremely personal, which may be a problem when it comes to ethics.\n\nMay potentially lead to some self-fulfilling prophecies where predicting dropout causes the dropout."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 4
    }
